reviews.review_text:
WHO IS THIS GAME FOR?

Someone looking to have casual space liberation fun, preferably with friends, and doesn't get worked up over grinding, bugs, or incomprehensible updates.

PROS:
- GOOD TIMES - game that's an absolutely frenetic blast with friends;
- KEEPS YOU DIVING - great base gameplay loop that moves through factions in new ways so that no one of them winds up stale;
- INTERESTING BUILDS - in some cases*, there are several ways to approach a single problem, giving players room to be creative;
- ACTIVE DEV - dev team is actively churning out new stuff**; 
- NOT WORST COMMUNITY - randos are, on average, less toxic garbage than other shooters;
- THIS IS THE WAY - nearly unlimited meme potential;

CONS:
- BUSTED AF - game's buggy as hell. I can't recall a single match where I didn't witness a bug, or a session where something just broke, and trust me when I say that everything can fail in this game. Straight-up game-breaking bugs are rare, but the game seriously requires some love and optimization that the developers are not focusing on with the required intensity;
- BAD UPDATES - (* and ** comments from above) new content and releases, while often pretty cool, are also frequently plagued by incoherent changes or worse - nerfs to the amount of fun the game allows you to have. See fuller comments below; 
- OBVIOUS, CREEPING MICROTRANSACTIONS - this game has six (yes, six) forms of currency that it uses to justify grinding. I've played for 200 hours and still haven't naturally unlocked all the ship upgrades available. You need 200 Rare Samples for 1 Level 5 ship upgrade, and on a good 30-40 minute match we're lucky to get 5-10, almost no chance with randos. Do the math. Also, there's dedicated sections of the new stuff that they release that is increasingly paywalled. Why are the new mechs behind a Warbond? When's the last time we got a Stratagem for free? Or even a silly cosmetic, for that matter? 
- WEIRDLY UNFINISHED SYSTEMS - These stand out so starkly against the microtransaction machine that is warbonds, and I honestly don't know if they're ever going to improve. Primary weapon customization is almost entirely aesthetic unless you grind a gun out to almost the final level to get an expanded mag that's actually useful, for example. Secondaries, stratagems have zero customization. The suits of armor can often look nice, but no customization there beyond which helmet you wear. No pre-set loadouts exist. No favorites exist. I want these things to be in the game, but at this point I'm afraid that they'd be set as available only for some premium currency.


FULL COMMENTS: It's painfully obvious that the devs don't play their own game, and they bizarrely don't hide this fact in their streams and Q&As. Desperately, desperately needed fixes are passed over in favor of pumping out new warbonds (translation for non-divers: microtransactions). Fun, quirky things the community discovers re: the game are often nerfed into the Shadow Realm. Power creep with newer stuff makes old stuff non-viable, and so you get these weird metas in a place where I want to be able to shotgun, flamethrower, gas, or snipe the required amount of Democracy into those dirty space fascists....but I can't. Good luck not bringing fire or lasers to Spore Swarm. I play from 7-10 difficulty, but it's distressing when there's straight up no counterplay to dropping into the middle of a bug pack that's snow'd out, immediately surrounds you, and gives you the slappy choppy. 

There's so much potential here, and it's heartbreaking to see it squandered. 

Edit: Why am I recommending this game, you ask? Because the core of a strong, replayable, silly over-the-shoulder shooter is here, and I continue to have fun with it to this day. The review bombing is ...well, feels a bit overwhelming, and it doesn't feel fair to just spit on a game I've spent this much time enjoying, even if recent trends are a bit of a bummer.

Are the cons frustrating? Sometimes. Is the development direction disappointing? Sure, we can't all be Larian, and as others have pointed out, the big downsides (at least IMO) to this game require a lot of context and background to unpack, whereas the positives don't to the same extent - fun is just fun. 

Also, let's be honest - the community here hasn't always been without scandal either. Doxxing folks, glazedivers that brainlessly praise everything the devs do (how are them Hive Guards looking?), anti-glazedivers that **** on what they perceive to be glazediving ...

This is a self-aware, hyper-patriotic parody of space fascism (which is why German/Japanese dubs slap so hard). Only people like Pete "0 for 0 pullups" Hegseth could take something like this seriously, and I don't know why they're doing so. 

It is, definitionally, a game. If you aren't having fun, then go find your new boo, my lads and lasses. And Democracy speed your step.
